ion to Irish Modernism presents a fresh perspective on received understandings of Irish modernism. The introduction draws connections between modernism in the arts and modernism as a resistant, liberal, relativist movement within the Catholic Church that was gathering momentum in the same period. In religion as in culture, resistance to orthodoxy has persisted, and for this reason this companion explores modernist heresies – cultural, aesthetic, critical, epistemological – that stretch back to the late nineteenth-century and forward to present day. Contributors widen the temporal, conceptual, generic, and geographical definitions of Irish modernism by investigating crosscurrents between literary form and cultural transformation through the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. The book enriches the canon of Irish modernism by recovering lesser-known works by both neglected and canonical writers, especially women poets and novelists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEnglish literaturexIrish authorsy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Art)zIreland. 0aModernism (Christian theology)zIreland. 0aModernism (Literature)zIreland. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh1 aBoynton, T. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColangelo, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnolly, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConrad, Kathryn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarcy, Ailbhe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllmann, Maud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalci, Eric, econtributor.4